{"summary": "Based on the action documents, several water level manipulation interventions have been studied on drained peatlands without planting. Rewetting peatlands by raising the water table (action ID 1756) was evaluated in 36 studies across bogs, fens, and other peatlands. This intervention typically caused drier grassland communities to be replaced by more wetland- or peatland-characteristic communities, with rewetted plots developing different plant communities compared to drained plots. Rewetting increased Sphagnum moss cover or abundance in 12 studies across multiple countries, though three studies reported mixed responses by species and two studies found no effect. The intervention increased cover of various herb groups, with particularly strong effects on sedges (increased in 13 of 15 studies), cottongrass (increased in 8 of 9 studies), and reeds/rushes (increased in 5 of 7 studies), while purple moor grass cover was typically reduced. Tree and shrub cover was generally reduced or unaffected by rewetting. Effects on overall plant species richness were mixed, with six studies reporting increases, five finding no effect, and one study reporting reduced diversity.

Irrigation of peatlands without planting (action ID 1859) was studied in only two investigations. In a Canadian bog, irrigation increased Sphagnum moss shoots after one growing season but had no effect after two seasons. In a German fen, irrigation led to colonization by wetland- and fen-characteristic herbs while cover of dryland grasses decreased.

Draining or replacing acidic water (action ID 1791) was evaluated in two fen studies in the Netherlands, showing mixed effects on Sphagnum moss and herb cover after 4-5 years depending on species and whether moss was also removed, though one study reported increased plant species richness.", "action_ids": ["1756","1859","1791"], "query": "What are the effects of different interventions designed to manipulate water levels on drained peatlands without planting?"}

